In my class, MAE 3240, we have been learning many of the fundamental concepts of heat transfer mechanics. On our recent homework assignment (number 5), I solidified a lot of my new knowledge and understanding of the use of fins to increase the surface area of a component and boost the convective heat transfer to the surrounding air. Additionally, by solving the first problem, I learned how to apply the fin equation to a 5x5 array. In this problem, we calculated the overall surface efficiency and constructed a thermal resistance network which allowed me to see how individual components—like contact resistance and slab conduction contribute to the total temperature drop of the heater. 

The second problem in the assignment introduced the new concept of transient heat transfer and using the Lumped Capacitance Method to understand a long wire submerged in an oil bath. I learned to first validate the model using the Biot number, to ensure that internal temperature gradients could be neglected. After, I was able to derive an expression expression for the wire temperature as a function of time. This assignment was very useful in solidifying my heat transfer knowledge and will help prepare me for my future work.

